5","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"1160–":"1160–Overleden","1160–Male":"1160–Overleden","1165–Female":"1165–Overleden","1185–Female":"1185–Overleden","1140–Male":"1140–Overleden","1140–Female":"1140–Overleden","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1160–":"1160–Deceased","1160–Male":"1160–Deceased","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","1185–Female":"1185–Deceased","1140–Male":"1140–Deceased","1140–Female":"1140–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Norton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places so called, from Old English <i>north</i> ‘north’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. In some cases it is a variant of   Norrington  .","Irish: altered form of   Naughton  , assimilated to the English name (see 1 above).","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of some similar (like-sounding) original Ashkenazic surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Norrington","meanings":["English:","(southeastern): from Norringtonend in Redbourn (Hertforshire), Northingtown Farm in Grimley (Worcestershire), or Norrington in Alvediston (Wiltshire). All three names are from Old English <i>north in tūne</i> ‘to the north of the village’.","possibly a variant of <b>Northampton</b>, a habitational name from the city of this name, which was named with Old English <i>north</i> ‘north’ + <i>hām</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘homestead, home farm’."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":55,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":64,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":99,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh Norton was born in 1160, in Newton, Yorkshire, England, his father, Roger de Coniers, was 20 and his mother, Mrs. Roger de Coniers, was 21. He married Mrs. Hugh Norton in 1185, in Newton, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1160–":"1160–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1160–":"1160–Kuollut","1160–Male":"1160–Kuollut","1165–Female":"1165–Kuollut","1185–Female":"1185–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1140–Female":"1140–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1160–":"1160–Décédé","1160–Male":"1160–Décédé","1165–Female":"1165–Décédée","1185–Female":"1185–Décédée","1140–Male":"1140–Décédé","1140–Female":"1140–Décédée","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Hugh Norton est né en 1160, à Newton, Everwyck, Angleterre, son père, Roger de Coniers, avait 20 ans et sa mère, Mrs. Roger de Coniers, avait 21 ans. Il a épousé Mrs. Hugh Norton en 1185, à Newton, Everwyck, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1160–":"1160–Verstorben","1160–Male":"1160–Verstorben","1165–Female":"1165–Verstorben","1185–Female":"1185–Verstorben","1140–Male":"1140–Verstorben","1140–Female":"1140–Verstorben","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1165":"1165","